WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.879
I work at RStudio, and I'm also RStudio's person on the Board of Directors of the R

00:00:17.879 --> 00:00:18.879
Consortium.

00:00:18.879 --> 00:00:25.959
So I'm here today in a dual capacity, and what I want to do is give you some idea of

00:00:25.959 --> 00:00:34.160
what the R Consortium is helping to make happen in medicine and pharma.

00:00:34.160 --> 00:00:44.119
So the R Consortium, we are a non-profit organization organized under the Linux Foundation with

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:45.119
three goals.

00:00:45.119 --> 00:00:52.119
I mean, we're here to promote the growth and development of R and the R community, to support

00:00:52.119 --> 00:00:59.520
the R Foundation, the people who develop R and take care of it, and also to enable

00:00:59.520 --> 00:01:05.540
the use of R in large-scale operations and organizations.

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:11.879
So what you see here are the companies that are presently members of the R Consortium.

00:01:11.879 --> 00:01:17.400
I particularly like to point out Genentech Roche, which has a new member, joined the

00:01:17.400 --> 00:01:20.680
consortium just this year.

00:01:20.680 --> 00:01:25.400
And I think, in part at least, their membership was inspired by some of the events that I'm

00:01:25.400 --> 00:01:28.739
going to tell you about today.

00:01:28.739 --> 00:01:31.680
So how do we accomplish these goals?

00:01:31.680 --> 00:01:41.879
We do it by supporting projects and initiatives that are mostly community-initiated.

00:01:41.879 --> 00:01:48.000
We go out twice a year with a call for proposals, and we award grants to proposals that are

00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.419
accepted.

00:01:49.419 --> 00:01:54.660
So far, in the three years or so that the consortium has been in existence, we have

00:01:54.660 --> 00:02:03.660
awarded over $740,000 in grants directly to community members who've submitted proposals.

00:02:03.660 --> 00:02:10.580
We sponsor conferences and working groups and other community initiatives like the R

00:02:10.580 --> 00:02:12.080
Ladies.

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:25.919
And we also help to organize what we call working groups, which are generally community-initiated

00:02:25.919 --> 00:02:30.759
projects that need organization and sometimes consensus building.

00:02:30.759 --> 00:02:39.039
So working groups are the way to try to organize the resources of the R community under the

00:02:39.039 --> 00:02:46.080
sponsorship of the consortium to get something done that maybe you can't do on your own or

00:02:46.080 --> 00:02:49.039
in your own company or with a small group.

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:56.559
So what I'm going to be talking about today are all R consortium working groups in process.

00:02:56.559 --> 00:02:58.960
So what's going on?

00:02:58.960 --> 00:03:04.960
And well, before I move on, let me emphasize that these initiatives that I'm talking about

00:03:04.960 --> 00:03:11.320
here are not something that was thought up by the board of directors of the R consortium.

00:03:11.320 --> 00:03:21.960
These are really grassroots community-started projects that were just come to fruition through

00:03:21.960 --> 00:03:30.360
the enthusiasm of the R champions in various companies throughout the world and who managed

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:37.240
to organize and get the people who are their employers and supervisors excited about what

00:03:37.240 --> 00:03:38.240
they're doing.

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:42.080
So let's look at some of these.

00:03:42.080 --> 00:03:43.679
So first is R and pharma.

00:03:43.679 --> 00:03:52.240
So R pharma started out last year, envisioned as an annual conference, the kind of complement

00:03:52.240 --> 00:04:01.240
to this huge gathering, a small kind of almost working group with the kind of environment

00:04:01.240 --> 00:04:09.080
where there's just people there to get actual work done and make progress.

00:04:09.080 --> 00:04:11.839
The conference itself is summarized here.

00:04:11.839 --> 00:04:21.040
You can see reading left to right, what you should notice is that the organizing committee

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.399
was made up of people from lots of different pharmaceutical companies and device companies.

00:04:26.399 --> 00:04:32.359
You can see in the middle graph there that there were even more companies who were attending

00:04:32.359 --> 00:04:34.119
the conference.

00:04:34.119 --> 00:04:42.839
We had keynote speakers from the FDA, so the FDA involvement, and the word cloud over there

00:04:42.839 --> 00:04:46.880
gives you an idea of some of the things that interested them.

00:04:46.880 --> 00:04:51.920
In particular, Shiny was on the minds of almost everybody.

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:58.519
More than half of the talks had Shiny mentioned them in some way or another.

00:04:58.519 --> 00:05:08.160
So just to emphasize that, what I'd like to show you here are a couple of projects that

00:05:08.160 --> 00:05:20.359
were presented at this R pharma conference, and in particular, this BioWarp application

00:05:20.359 --> 00:05:21.920
from Roche.

00:05:21.920 --> 00:05:25.859
It was written up in the R views blog.

00:05:25.859 --> 00:05:28.799
You can see it under how to build the Shiny truck.

00:05:28.799 --> 00:05:35.880
It's 100,000 lines of code, and what you should take away from here is that it is a production

00:05:35.880 --> 00:05:46.899
Shiny application that totally permeates all of the regulatory tasks that go on in

00:05:46.899 --> 00:05:48.779
order to get a drug out.

00:05:48.779 --> 00:05:57.880
So here we have, you can see here that they have, they're advancing the use of R and Shiny

00:05:57.880 --> 00:06:04.519
in an environment that is extremely important to how Roche operates.

00:06:04.519 --> 00:06:16.720
Another talk that was presented at the same conference, R pharma, also by a Roche person,

00:06:16.720 --> 00:06:22.660
emphasized the kind of environment that they're putting together there, and it gives you some

00:06:22.660 --> 00:06:29.320
insight into the kind of nitty gritty steps that need to get done in order to go through

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.239
their workflow.

00:06:31.239 --> 00:06:38.160
In particular, they call out the creation of tables and particular formats that have

00:06:38.160 --> 00:06:44.440
to go into regulatory submissions, a pipeline for producing those tables, and you have to

00:06:44.440 --> 00:06:49.480
have a modular framework to keep that all happening in a dynamic way.

00:06:49.480 --> 00:07:00.959
So Shiny and the pharmaceutical industry are, you know, it's an extremely important

00:07:00.959 --> 00:07:08.959
and embedded part now of how they're doing drug development.

00:07:08.959 --> 00:07:15.320
A parallel initiative, this is another working group, organized about the same time, this

00:07:15.320 --> 00:07:25.480
project was awarded last year, initiated through this, PSI is a worldwide organization

00:07:25.480 --> 00:07:32.040
of statisticians working in the pharmaceutical industry, and they had a special methods working

00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:40.000
group, and what they're trying to produce is a validated hub for R packages.

00:07:40.000 --> 00:07:44.899
Validated in a way that's particularly important for the pharmaceutical industry.

00:07:44.899 --> 00:07:45.899
So what does it mean?

00:07:45.899 --> 00:07:51.220
You know, validation can mean lots of things, and what they're struggling with is to come

00:07:51.220 --> 00:08:03.899
up with a concept and a workflow to help people build packages and repositories that would

00:08:03.899 --> 00:08:12.500
contain just those packages that are validated according to their kind of particular environment

00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:14.059
in their company.

00:08:14.220 --> 00:08:21.059
So what they'll do, the goals are, in the beginning, is to come up with an idea of validation

00:08:21.059 --> 00:08:25.859
that seems appropriate for the regulatory environment that they're in, to develop a

00:08:25.859 --> 00:08:33.099
concept of risk that might be associated with a package, and to provide standards for how

00:08:33.099 --> 00:08:43.380
to go about validating packages, and hopefully it will result in perhaps a repository that's

00:08:43.380 --> 00:08:48.380
out in the open that will contain packages that have been validated this way.

00:08:48.380 --> 00:08:55.419
But I think more importantly, companies will use it behind their firewalls to create repositories

00:08:55.419 --> 00:09:05.179
that have packages that are meaningfully validated according to their particular company standards.

00:09:05.179 --> 00:09:06.940
So this is a big deal.

00:09:06.940 --> 00:09:12.700
You can see that these are just a sample of some of the companies that are involved, and

00:09:12.700 --> 00:09:18.900
it takes, you know, it goes across the spectrum of the pharmaceutical industry.

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:27.260
I'm very hopeful that this kind of thing will set a precedent for other kinds of validation

00:09:27.260 --> 00:09:28.979
in different industries.

00:09:28.979 --> 00:09:34.979
I think perhaps people working in financial organizations will find this of use.

00:09:34.979 --> 00:09:40.780
They'll have to change the details, but with any luck, we'll be able to produce something

00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:48.099
that would be easy to propagate throughout different industries, and hopefully the R

00:09:48.099 --> 00:09:56.659
Consortium could be of help in making that happen.

00:09:56.659 --> 00:10:05.219
Now in a parallel effort that's going on, is the last year, we also started an R in

00:10:05.219 --> 00:10:12.739
medicine conference, and originally I thought, you know, why one conference, why not one

00:10:12.739 --> 00:10:22.380
conference to deal both with pharma and medicine, but the two groups were very, very adamant

00:10:22.380 --> 00:10:26.940
that they all needed their own space, and as it turns out, it would not have worked

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:33.299
to just have one conference, because these working groups are really working at a level

00:10:33.340 --> 00:10:39.140
of detail that's specific to the particular kinds of problems that they're solving.

00:10:39.140 --> 00:10:54.020
So the R in medicine 2018 was really focused on clinicians and clinical uses of R, and

00:10:54.020 --> 00:10:56.380
something that I did not expect.

00:10:56.419 --> 00:11:03.820
We had many of the attendees were MDs, PhD MDs, who were either teaching themselves R,

00:11:03.820 --> 00:11:10.460
or in some cases R in statistics all at the same time, and here are a couple of examples

00:11:10.460 --> 00:11:15.140
of the kinds of applications that they were talking about.

00:11:15.140 --> 00:11:22.659
This was presented by Rob Tibshirani of Stanford, and what you see is a very practical problem

00:11:22.659 --> 00:11:30.419
of predicting blood platelet usage, a tremendously, you know, valuable resource.

00:11:30.419 --> 00:11:36.940
People give their blood for this, and they only have the packets, the platelets are only

00:11:36.940 --> 00:11:42.260
usable for three days, so they have about a five-day shelf life, two days for getting

00:11:42.260 --> 00:11:48.140
everything in the system, and the graphs there you see are indicative of the kind of waste

00:11:48.140 --> 00:11:49.940
over time.

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:59.219
So there was a tremendous amount of enthusiasm, not only to help the human problem of saving

00:11:59.219 --> 00:12:04.340
this valuable resource, but for saving money, to not have these things go to waste.

00:12:04.340 --> 00:12:09.979
And the solution that they came up with, which is up and running right now, I believe still

00:12:09.979 --> 00:12:18.140
in parallel with the original system, was to forecast the prediction of how many units

00:12:18.140 --> 00:12:19.440
to order.

00:12:19.440 --> 00:12:23.760
So what they did was they changed the, you know, the nature of the question while they

00:12:23.760 --> 00:12:31.760
were working, and it came up that it was, turned out to be a kind of standard convex

00:12:31.760 --> 00:12:37.559
optimization problem, a linear programming problem, solved, I think they used it using

00:12:37.559 --> 00:12:47.880
the CVXR package in R, which is really its own kind of DSL for formulating and solving

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:51.599
convex optimization problems.

00:12:51.599 --> 00:12:55.479
And they're hopeful that they'll be able to save a considerable amount of money.

00:12:55.479 --> 00:13:04.440
So this package is, the link there, you can see the actual analysis, but the package CVXR

00:13:04.440 --> 00:13:10.840
I think might be of use to many of you.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:19.479
And the next application here I think is particularly interesting for a group of people,

00:13:19.479 --> 00:13:23.679
you know, data scientists who are used to machine learning.

00:13:23.679 --> 00:13:28.760
And what we have here are fast and fugal trees.

00:13:28.760 --> 00:13:32.400
They're a special highly restricted kind of decision tree.

00:13:32.400 --> 00:13:39.520
It's a standard, one way to look at it, it's a standard classification algorithm.

00:13:39.520 --> 00:13:44.080
But it's highly optimized for decision making.

00:13:44.080 --> 00:13:49.799
So you can see that every branch of the tree terminates in at least one leaf.

00:13:49.799 --> 00:13:52.640
So there's a decision to be made.

00:13:52.640 --> 00:14:02.080
And this is the kind of thing that is particularly appealing to doctors who have to do a kind

00:14:02.080 --> 00:14:05.080
of very quick decision making.

00:14:05.080 --> 00:14:11.280
And what they'd like to have is a tool that is sophisticated, can help them make the good

00:14:11.280 --> 00:14:17.320
decision, but is not complicated and easy to explain and interpret.

00:14:17.320 --> 00:14:20.479
So these trees seem to be doing pretty well.

00:14:20.479 --> 00:14:28.679
And they provide an example of, you know, almost every statistical inference problem

00:14:28.679 --> 00:14:32.200
can be conceptualized as a decision problem.

00:14:32.320 --> 00:14:38.159
And sometimes going back and forth between the two when you're doing this kind of analysis

00:14:38.159 --> 00:14:40.159
can be really fruitful.

00:14:40.159 --> 00:14:45.799
And I think what you'll see with this fast and frugal tree kind of approach is that you

00:14:45.799 --> 00:14:55.280
don't need necessarily the best algorithm in order to make the, you know, to have a

00:14:55.280 --> 00:14:57.320
successful outcome.

00:14:57.320 --> 00:15:02.159
You don't have to have the thing that perfectly beats everything else on the ROC curve.

00:15:02.159 --> 00:15:07.359
What you need to do is have an algorithm that's good enough to make the right decision.

00:15:07.359 --> 00:15:16.000
So this is a, I like it because it's at the interface of machine learning, decision making,

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:20.440
very, you know, in a fast and dynamic environment.

00:15:20.440 --> 00:15:28.799
And I think it could be helpful for all data scientists to delve deep enough into a problem

00:15:28.880 --> 00:15:36.679
to see whether it can be conceptualized as a decision problem and not necessarily a mechanistic

00:15:36.679 --> 00:15:41.200
approach to seeing how to grind through a solution.

00:15:41.200 --> 00:15:45.599
So the package itself, FFtrees, is up on CRAN.

00:15:45.599 --> 00:15:50.000
And you know, I review a lot of packages, R packages, every month.

00:15:50.000 --> 00:15:51.799
I blog about that.

00:15:51.799 --> 00:15:57.400
And I particularly like this one because of the extensive documentation.

00:15:57.400 --> 00:16:02.760
I would like to offer it as an example of an R package where it seems to me that the

00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:08.760
authors put almost as much work or maybe more work into the documentation than into the

00:16:08.760 --> 00:16:09.919
package itself.

00:16:09.919 --> 00:16:12.440
So I encourage everybody to look at that.

00:16:12.440 --> 00:16:16.640
And you can see what I have here is a diagram that's a standard one out of their vignette.

00:16:16.640 --> 00:16:21.719
They took a lot of attention to presenting the work and helping people think through

00:16:21.719 --> 00:16:24.039
the analysis that they're presenting.

00:16:24.080 --> 00:16:27.159
So I highly recommend that.

00:16:31.280 --> 00:16:42.159
Now, I want to say a couple of words about what we might be looking at for 2019.

00:16:42.159 --> 00:16:51.760
This comes from Joseph Chu, an MD at the neonatal intensive care facility at the Massachusetts

00:16:51.760 --> 00:16:53.760
General Hospital for Children.

00:16:53.760 --> 00:17:00.080
And he describes this, this actually is an email he sent to me where he calls it his

00:17:00.080 --> 00:17:04.239
glorified chart review program, his process for chart review.

00:17:04.239 --> 00:17:08.199
So are there physicians out here?

00:17:08.199 --> 00:17:08.920
Yes.

00:17:08.920 --> 00:17:12.599
So I'm sure then you'll relate to this kind of thing.

00:17:12.599 --> 00:17:17.839
Not only his sense of humor, but it's pretty amazing the amount of sophistication that he

00:17:17.839 --> 00:17:25.199
has put into taking data from the epic, you know, the system that is a given that they

00:17:25.199 --> 00:17:32.839
have to work with and getting it into a place where you can manipulate it with tidy

00:17:32.839 --> 00:17:38.719
techniques and put it out there in terms of flash for, you know, flex dashboards and

00:17:39.079 --> 00:17:40.520
reproducible reports.

00:17:41.239 --> 00:17:47.000
So I think this is the kind of thing that's setting a standard for doing like reproducible

00:17:47.000 --> 00:17:51.800
medicine at a micro level at the doctor individual clinician level.

00:17:52.040 --> 00:17:59.760
Well, it's a I hope that we can learn a lot more from Joseph's participation in the

00:17:59.760 --> 00:18:03.880
organizing committee for 2019.

00:18:05.160 --> 00:18:12.079
Another group that's doing an incredibly interesting and prolific work with shiny is the

00:18:12.079 --> 00:18:15.719
Cleveland Clinic Department of Quantitative Health Services.

00:18:16.719 --> 00:18:22.719
All of these are different risk calculators, shiny based risk calculators that they have up

00:18:22.800 --> 00:18:23.439
online.

00:18:23.839 --> 00:18:27.040
All of these different diseases, they're up there for everybody.

00:18:27.599 --> 00:18:32.640
Here's an example of one with, you know, the disclaimer.

00:18:34.400 --> 00:18:39.520
Don't take this as medical advice, but it's a beautiful kind of thing that can help anyone

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:45.880
who's interested in the disease and their particular where they might be at risk can

00:18:45.880 --> 00:18:46.760
access.

00:18:47.400 --> 00:18:50.880
Again, it's all shiny based and these are production.

00:18:50.920 --> 00:18:55.800
Obviously, these are production applications up there, you know, 24-7.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:03.319
So I'm hoping, in fact, that we will be able to interview some of the people involved at

00:19:03.319 --> 00:19:08.560
this and I'll publish it on the Our Views blog when that happens.

00:19:10.280 --> 00:19:18.479
And then a final example of analyzing glaucoma.

00:19:20.160 --> 00:19:23.079
Has anybody here ever taken a visual field test?

00:19:24.800 --> 00:19:25.319
Yes.

00:19:25.760 --> 00:19:31.760
So glaucoma is a disease that, you know, one of the leading causes of blindness.

00:19:31.760 --> 00:19:37.439
Prevalence is about 4 percent in the population of people 40 to 80 years old.

00:19:37.479 --> 00:19:38.439
So I'm in there.

00:19:39.079 --> 00:19:41.920
And it's a degenerative progressive disease.

00:19:41.959 --> 00:19:44.680
You know, your optic nerve deteriorates.

00:19:44.800 --> 00:19:49.800
So one of the ways they measure this is by making you take this visual field test.

00:19:49.800 --> 00:19:55.719
So you sit there and you've got your eyes, one eye at a time, focused on the dot in the

00:19:55.719 --> 00:19:56.239
center.

00:19:56.599 --> 00:19:58.599
And you've got this little clicker in your hand.

00:19:59.199 --> 00:20:03.920
And it's really nerve wracking because what you're supposed to do is click every time

00:20:03.920 --> 00:20:05.199
you see a flash of light.

00:20:06.079 --> 00:20:09.839
And, you know, the first thing that happens is you say, where's that flash going to come

00:20:09.839 --> 00:20:10.160
from?

00:20:10.199 --> 00:20:14.880
So the flashes of light are randomly distributed around your visual field.

00:20:14.880 --> 00:20:19.439
And the most annoying part is that they vary in intensity.

00:20:19.439 --> 00:20:25.079
So sometimes it's a sharp speck and sometimes you don't even know that you really saw it.

00:20:25.599 --> 00:20:28.920
But what they're doing is measuring the differential light intensity.

00:20:29.880 --> 00:20:35.359
So your sensitivity to the changes in light at various parts of the visual field.

00:20:36.199 --> 00:20:39.680
And there's something called a Humphrey analyzer.

00:20:40.160 --> 00:20:45.199
And what this does is map like 54 sections of the visual field.

00:20:47.239 --> 00:20:49.839
52 if you take out where your blind spots are.

00:20:50.160 --> 00:20:51.400
And it produces a number.

00:20:51.439 --> 00:20:54.880
So you get an individual number for a test.

00:20:55.359 --> 00:21:02.560
And what you see here are time series in these little boxes because they represent

00:21:02.599 --> 00:21:04.640
longitudinal data for a patient.

00:21:05.359 --> 00:21:11.239
And what these statisticians are doing, Birchuk at Duke and Warren at Yale, is they're

00:21:11.239 --> 00:21:19.479
building models to predict the progression of the disease by analyzing the changes in

00:21:19.479 --> 00:21:25.400
these visual field records using spatial statistics in a very sophisticated way.

00:21:25.439 --> 00:21:32.319
Because they need to measure the nearness not only in terms of where these boxes are

00:21:32.319 --> 00:21:40.319
adjacent to each other but how they actually go into the optic nerve which is not the

00:21:40.319 --> 00:21:40.800
same.

00:21:40.839 --> 00:21:42.839
It's a different kind of mapping.

00:21:42.880 --> 00:21:49.160
So they do that and they're using these packages WAMBL-R and this new SPCP package.

00:21:49.959 --> 00:21:55.000
And they've developed models for the progression of the disease again at an

00:21:55.000 --> 00:21:56.040
individual level.

00:21:56.079 --> 00:22:04.000
So this is the kind of thing that if you had this disease you might go to your your

00:22:04.000 --> 00:22:11.640
physician and say would this be useful in tracking the progression of glaucoma for me

00:22:12.280 --> 00:22:15.439
over the course of my lifetime.

00:22:15.760 --> 00:22:22.920
So you can find that you can find a series of three blog posts written on our views

00:22:22.959 --> 00:22:25.560
describing this in some considerable detail.

00:22:25.959 --> 00:22:29.119
And of course the packages and the statistics speak for themselves.

00:22:29.160 --> 00:22:30.280
You can find them on CRAN.

00:22:33.439 --> 00:22:39.239
Well that's basically what I want to say and I want to leave you with an observation

00:22:39.800 --> 00:22:41.359
and a call to action.

00:22:41.479 --> 00:22:50.479
The observation is that all of these efforts are accomplished by both people and and

00:22:50.560 --> 00:22:54.560
organizations getting involved in something bigger than themselves.

00:22:56.400 --> 00:23:01.239
So when you think about the R Consortium you could you could think about it as kind of

00:23:01.239 --> 00:23:07.160
the gateway for companies to become involved in the R community.

00:23:07.160 --> 00:23:12.880
So just as you may write packages and contribute to the community in various ways

00:23:13.239 --> 00:23:19.000
this is a possibility for companies to organize contributions in a way that are much

00:23:19.000 --> 00:23:23.119
bigger than an individual can mount on his or her own efforts.

